# Three.js Scene Graph Traversal

## Overview
Three.js scenes are hierarchical. Groups and meshes form a tree. Each node has local "'`position`, `rotation`, `scale`, and a computed `matrixWorld` that combines all ancestor transforms.

## Key APIs
- `scene.updateMatrixWorld(true)` — force-update all world matrices
- `group.traverse(callback)` — visit every descendant
- `mesh.matrixWorld` — 4x4 matrix from local to world space
- `geometry.clone().applyMatrix4(matrix)` — bake transform into vertex positions

## Hierarchy Pattern
```js
const root = createScene();
const scene = new THREE.Scene();
scene.add(root);
scene.updateMatrixWorld(true);

root.traverse(child => {
  if (child.isMesh) {
    const worldGeo = child.geometry.clone();
    worldGeo.applyMatrix4(child.matrixWorld);
    // worldGeo now has vertices in world space
  }
});
```

## Important Notes
- Always call `updateMatrixWorld(true)` before reading `matrixWorld`
- `geometry.applyMatrix4()` modifies vertex positions in-place on the clone
- BufferGeometry stores positions in `Float32Array` via `getAttribute('"'position')"'`
EOF
