# OBJ File Export from Three.js

## OBJ Format Basics
"'```
v x y z          # vertex position
vn nx ny nz      # vertex normal (optional)
vt u v           # texture coordinate (optional)
f v1 v2 v3       # face (1-based indices)
o object_name    # object name header
```

## Manual OBJ Writing
```javascript
function writeOBJ(filepath, positions, faces) {
    let lines = [];
    for (const p of positions) {
        lines.push(`v ${p.x} ${p.y} ${p.z}`);
    }
    for (const f of faces) {
        lines.push(`f ${f[0]+1} ${f[1]+1} ${f[2]+1}`); // 1-based
    }
    fs.writeFileSync(filepath, lines.join('"'\\n') + '\\n');
}
"'```

## Handling Indexed vs Non-Indexed Geometry
```javascript
function getFaces(geometry) {
    const faces = [];
    const index = geometry.index;
    if (index) {
        for (let i = 0; i < index.count; i += 3)
            faces.push([index.getX(i), index.getX(i+1), index.getX(i+2)]);
    } else {
        const count = geometry.attributes.position.count;
        for (let i = 0; i < count; i += 3)
            faces.push([i, i+1, i+2]);
    }
    return faces;
}
```

## Using Three.js OBJExporter
```javascript
import { OBJExporter } from '"'three/examples/jsm/exporters/OBJExporter.js';
const exporter = new OBJExporter();
const objString = exporter.parse(scene); // uses matrixWorld internally
"'```
The OBJExporter always applies `mesh.matrixWorld` to vertex positions.

## Merging Geometries for Link Export
Concatenate vertex arrays with face index offsets:
```javascript
function mergeGeometries(meshDataList) {
    let allPos = [], allFaces = [], offset = 0;
    for (const { positions, faces } of meshDataList) {
        allPos.push(...positions);
        for (const f of faces)
            allFaces.push([f[0]+offset, f[1]+offset, f[2]+offset]);
        offset += positions.length;
    }
    return { positions: allPos, faces: allFaces };
}
```
