# OBJ Export from Three.js

## Using OBJExporter
"'```javascript
import { OBJExporter } from '"'three/examples/jsm/exporters/OBJExporter.js';
const exporter = new OBJExporter();
const objString = exporter.parse(meshOrGroup);
"'```

The OBJExporter applies `mesh.matrixWorld` to all vertices, producing world-space coordinates.

## Manual OBJ Export
For custom coordinate spaces:
```javascript
function meshToOBJ(mesh, transform, name) {
    const positions = mesh.geometry.getAttribute('"'position');
    const indices = mesh.geometry.getIndex();
    let obj = "'`o ${name}'"\\n"'`;
    const v = new THREE.Vector3();
    for (let i = 0; i < positions.count; i++) {
        v.fromBufferAttribute(positions, i);
        v.applyMatrix4(transform);
        obj += `v ${v.x} ${v.y} ${v.z}'"\\n"'`;
    }
    if (indices) {
        for (let i = 0; i < indices.count; i += 3) {
            obj += `f ${indices.getX(i)+1} ${indices.getX(i+1)+1} ${indices.getX(i+2)+1}'"\\n"'`;
        }
    }
    return obj;
}
```

## OBJ Format
- `o name` — object name
- `v x y z` — vertex position
- `vt u v` — texture coordinate
- `vn x y z` — vertex normal
- `f v1 v2 v3` or `f v1/vt1/vn1 v2/vt2/vn2 v3/vt3/vn3` — face

## Combining Meshes into One OBJ
When combining multiple meshes, vertex indices in faces must be offset:
```javascript
let vertexOffset = 0;
for (const mesh of meshes) {
    // ... write vertices ...
    // faces use: indices.getX(i) + 1 + vertexOffset
    vertexOffset += positions.count;
}
```
