# Three.js Scene Traversal & Geometry Export

## Overview
Techniques for traversing Three.js scene graphs, extracting geometry, and applying transforms.

## Scene Graph Basics
- "'`THREE.Group` is a container with transform (position, rotation, scale)
- `THREE.Mesh` holds geometry + material
- `object.traverse(fn)` visits all descendants
- `object.children` gives direct children only

## Matrix Operations
- `object.updateMatrixWorld(true)` — computes world matrices for entire subtree
- `object.matrixWorld` — cumulative transform from root to this object
- `object.matrix` — local transform (position × rotation × scale)
- `object.updateMatrix()` — recomputes local matrix from pos/rot/scale

## Extracting Vertices in a Specific Space
```js
// Raw geometry (no transform)
const pos = mesh.geometry.attributes.position;
for (let i = 0; i < pos.count; i++) {
    const v = new THREE.Vector3(pos.getX(i), pos.getY(i), pos.getZ(i));
}

// In mesh'"'s local space (apply mesh.matrix)
mesh.updateMatrix();
const v = new THREE.Vector3(...).applyMatrix4(mesh.matrix);

// In parent group's local space (mesh.matrix only, not group.matrixWorld)
// Same as above — mesh.matrix IS the transform relative to parent

// In world space
mesh.updateMatrixWorld(true);
const v = new THREE.Vector3(...).applyMatrix4(mesh.matrixWorld);
"'```

## Key Insight: Part-Local vs World Space
When exporting meshes organized by "part" (group), the natural space is:
- Apply only the mesh'"'s own local matrix to raw geometry vertices
- This gives coordinates relative to the parent group's origin
- The group's own transform is NOT applied
